I also faced this problem in my project. I store two classes/types of =
objects in the index: topics and messages (it's a forum search engine).

My very simple object/relation mapping is a class is called =
LuceneBridge:
public class LuceneBridge {
    // Object --> Document mapping
    public Document toDocument(Message m) { .. }
    public Document toDocument(Topic t) { .. }

    public Hit toHit(Document d, float score) {=20
      if(d.getField("type").stringValue().compareTo("topic")) =3D=3D 0) =
{
          return new TopicHit(d, score);
      } else {
          return new MessageHit(d, score);
      }
}

As you can see I wrap the hits in a new class called Hit. I can wrap =
some extra logic in TopicHit and MessageHit class (for example to get =
back Date, int, long values instead of String).

My goal was to package all indexing logic in one class.

peter

> -----Original Message-----
> From: Kelvin Tan [mailto:kelvin@relevanz.com]
> Sent: Thursday, April 04, 2002 4:13 AM
> To: lucene-user@jakarta.apache.org
> Subject: Objects as search results
>=20
>=20
> Here's a topic which to my recollection (surprisingly) hasn't=20
> been brought
> up: Assuming development in an object-oriented environment,=20
> it's a fair
> assumption that the eventual target of searching is an object. How are
> developers making this happen?
>=20
> Are all fields of the objects indexed and displayed=20
> accordingly (this means
> that the Document essentially takes the place of the object for search
> results. bad idea IMHO)? Is there some way for the object to be
> instantiated, then populated? How are these objects then=20
> displayed as search
> results?
>=20
> Here are some comments I have:
>=20
> a) Documents shouldn't be used for displaying search results.=20
> To do so would
> be inflexible and limit the type of data displayed as results=20
> to the fields
> in a document. This means that if you wish to display more=20
> information, more
> information has to be added to the document. This somewhat=20
> violates the
> purpose of the document, I think, which is to provide an=20
> abstraction of a
> atomic collection of searched/indexed fields. You may be able=20
> to get away
> with it for simple applications, but I don't think it's a good idea.
>=20
> Ideally, objects should be used to display the results then,=20
> since that's
> what a result represents. I use Velocity, so this is easy for=20
> me. I retrieve
> the objects as a collection (somehow), and stuff them into=20
> the Context for
> rendering.
>=20
> b) Different types of objects obviously have different types=20
> of metadata.
> How can the different fields for each object be displayed,=20
> when the types of
> objects to be indexed aren't fixed? (I use fields and metadata
> interchangeably, so metadata is really a collection of fields=20
> of an object)
>=20
> c) I use Torque, so object instantiation and population is a=20
> pretty easy
> thing. I have no real solution to others, who don't have some=20
> kind of O/R
> tool of sorts.
>=20
> I have addressed these points to my satisfaction in a current=20
> app, but they
> are terribly reliant on a specific combination (Torque and=20
> Velocity). I'm
> really interested to know how other developers have approached this.
>=20
> Regards,
> Kelvin Tan
>=20
> Relevanz Pte Ltd
> http://www.relevanz.com
>=20
> 180B Bencoolen St.
