> -----Original Message-----
> From: Peter Carlson [mailto:carlson@bookandhammer.com]
> Sent: Thursday, April 11, 2002 4:35 PM
> To: Lucene Users List
> Subject: Re: Normalization of Documents
>=20
>=20
> Hi,
>=20
> These types of questions/discussions should be on the users=20
> list, not dev
> list, please.
>=20
OK

>=20
> Just for the record, the Lucene scoring is not as simple as just a %.
> From the FAQ.
>=20
> For the record, Lucene's scoring algorithm is, roughly:
>=20
>   score_d =3D sum_t( tf_q * idf_t / norm_q * tf_d * idf_t / norm_d_t)
What I would like:

  score_d =3D sum_t( tf_q * idf_t / norm_q * tf_d * idf_t / norm_d_t) * =
p_value_d

where:
p_value_d : predefined value of document calculated at indexing time (0 =
< p_value_d <=3D 1)

in the API:
option 1:
writer =3D new IndexWriter(..)
writer.addDocument(doc, 0.45);

option 2 (I think better)

Document d =3D new Document();
d.setValue(0.45);
d.addField(..);
writer.addDocument();

peter



> =20
> where:
>   score_d   : score for document d
>   sum_t     : sum for all terms t
>   tf_q      : the square root of the frequency of t in the query
>   tf_d      : the square root of the frequency of t in d
>   idf_t     : log(numDocs/docFreq_t+1) + 1.0
>   numDocs   : number of documents in index
>   docFreq_t : number of documents containing t
>   norm_q    : sqrt(sum_t((tf_q*idf_t)^2))
>   norm_d_t  : square root of number of tokens in d in the=20
> same field as t
>=20
> (I hope that's right!)
>=20
> [Doug later added...]
>=20
> Make that:
>  =20
>   score_d =3D sum_t(tf_q * idf_t / norm_q * tf_d * idf_t /=20
> norm_d_t * boost_t)
> * coord_q_d
>=20
> where
>=20
>   boost_t    : the user-specified boost for term t
>   coord_q_d  : number of terms in both query and document /=20
> number of terms
> in query
>=20
> The coordination factor gives an AND-like boost to documents=20
> that contain,
> e.g., all three terms in a three word query over those that=20
> contain just two
> of the words.
>=20
>=20
>=20
> Although this may still not be what you want. You should be=20
> able to replace
> the scoring mechanism with your own. The problem you might run into is
> getting the document data (such as date) will slow down your=20
> search speed
> dramatically.
>=20
> Do you know about any solutions (Academic or free) that=20
> provide this concept
> extraction. I've heard of a group in the UK who worked on=20
> something like
> this.
>=20
> --Peter
>=20
>=20
>=20
> On 4/11/02 6:51 AM, "Hal=E1csy P=E9ter" <halacsy.peter@axelero.com> =
wrote:
>=20
> > Extracting concept is not too easy thing and I don't think=20
> you can implement a
> > language/context/document type independent solution.=20
> Filtering only important
> > terms of a text (and not index all text as in modern full=20
> text indexing
> > system) is one of the most important area of IR. A lot of=20
> project worked on
> > this topic but nowadays it's not too important because we=20
> can index every
> > terms if we want (cheaper and faster disk, lot of CPU).
> >=20
> > I think in lucene the the term's % of the document
> > (NUMBER_OF_WORDS_IN_THE_DOCUMENT /=20
> NUMBER_OF_QUERY_TERM_ACCURENCE )is
> > overweighted in some case. I would like to tune it if I could.
> >=20
> > Document scoring could provide solution for me and I think=20
> for Melissa as
> > well. I think it's a very important feature of a modern IR=20
> system. For example
> > Melissa would use it to score the documents based on link=20
> popularity (or
> > impact factor/citation frequency). In my project I should=20
> score documents on
> > their length and their age (more recent document is more=20
> valuable and very old
> > documents are as valuable as very new in my archive).
> >=20
> > peter
> >=20
> >> -----Original Message-----
> >> From: Peter Carlson [mailto:carlson@bookandhammer.com]
